Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Segments", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.956548125013696*^9, 3.956548139909809*^9}, {
   3.956837876881384*^9, 3.956837878865776*^9}, {3.956838225005312*^9, 
   3.956838225165234*^9}, {3.957507785945368*^9, 3.957507787784127*^9}, {
   3.957511475075093*^9, 3.957511476273613*^9}, 
   3.958047065238449*^9},ExpressionUUID->"c0539691-decf-8e4b-b915-\
0c3928f2b4b6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", "\"\< \n\nThe complex proper-time contour u(r) is parametrized \
by a real r, rIn<r<rOut, \nand is split into several straight-line segments. \
\nAlong each segment, u'(r)=\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[ExponentialE]\), \
SubscriptBox[\(\[ImaginaryI]\[CurlyPhi]\), \(j\)]]\) with constant \
\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(\[CurlyPhi]\), \(j\)]\) for \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(r\), \
\(j\)]\)<r<\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(r\), \(j + 1\)]\). \n\nThis is explained in:\n\
\nP. Semren and G.~Torgrimsson,\n``Worldline instantons for nonperturbative \
particle production by space and time dependent gravitational fields''\nPhys. \
Rev. D \!\(\*StyleBox[\"113\",FontWeight->\"Bold\"]\), 056005 (2026)\n\n\>\"",
   "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.991039334044161*^9, 3.9910395174132175`*^9}, {
   3.9910430889812317`*^9, 3.991043107574362*^9}, {3.991043212773245*^9, 
   3.9910432750179214`*^9}, 3.9910433785863895`*^9, {3.991046134458721*^9, 
   3.9910461630844154`*^9}, {3.991046194484373*^9, 
   3.9910462083989277`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"31d2f040-1f0f-264d-a5a8-\
1cc488e258e5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", 
  RowBox[{"\"\<\n\nThe Newton-Raphson method used by FindRoot determines the \
values of \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(x\), \(\[Mu]\)]\)[0] (and in general \
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(x\), \(.\)], \(\[Mu]\)]\)[0]) for which \
zero=0, \nwhere zero is the direct output of segments[].\n\nsegments[] gives \
the instanton solution as indirect outputs, \ne.g. tFull[r] for t(r), and the \
automatically determined integration range rIn<r<rOut.\n\nFor generic values \
of the asymptotic momenta of the antiparticle and particle:\n\
\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(x\), \(.\)], \
\(\[Mu]\)]\)(-\[Infinity])=-\!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(q\), \(\[Mu]\)]\) and \!\(\
\*SuperscriptBox[OverscriptBox[\(x\), \(.\)], \(\[Mu]\)]\)(+\[Infinity])=\!\(\
\*SuperscriptBox[\(p\), \(\[Mu]\)]\).\n\nFor example, in D=2:\n\
zeroIn[Q_,dQ_]:={Re[-dQ[[2]]]-q,Im[dQ[[2]]]}; \
zeroOut[Q_,dQ_]:={Re[dQ[[2]]]-p,Im[dQ[[2]]]};\n\nFor the saddle-point values \
of the asymptotic momenta, p=\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(p\), \(s\)]\) and \
q=\!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(q\), \(s\)]\):\n\
zeroIn[Q_,dQ_]:={Im[Q[[2]]-\!\(\*FractionBox[\(dQ[[\(2\)\(]\)]\), \(dQ[[\(1\)\
\(]\)]\)]\)Q[[1]]],Im[dQ[[2]]]}; \
zeroOut[Q_,dQ_]:={Im[Q[[2]]-\!\(\*FractionBox[\(dQ[[\(2\)\(]\)]\), \
\(dQ[[\(1\)\(]\)]\)]\)Q[[1]]],Im[dQ[[2]]]};\n\nThis condition is explained \
in:\n\nG. Degli Esposti and G. Torgrimsson,\n``Worldline instantons for the \
momentum spectrum of Schwinger pair production in spacetime dependent \
fields''\nPhys. Rev. D \!\(\*StyleBox[\"107\",FontWeight->\"Bold\"]\), 056019 \
(2023)\n\nG. Degli Esposti and G. Torgrimsson,\n``Momentum spectrum of \
Schwinger pair production in four-dimensional e-dipole fields''\nPhys. Rev. D \
\!\(\*StyleBox[\"109\",FontWeight->\"Bold\"]\), 016013 (2024)\n\nG. Degli \
Esposti and G. Torgrimsson,\n``Momentum spectrum of nonlinear Breit-Wheeler \
pair production in spacetime fields''\nPhys. Rev. D \
\!\(\*StyleBox[\"110\",FontWeight->\"Bold\"]\), 076017 (2024)\n\n\n\
compIn=\>\"", 
   "no", "\"\<: \nThe antiparticle half of the instanton is not computed. \n\
This option can be used, for example, when symmetry implies x(0)=0, so that \
only t(0) needs to be determined.\n\ncomp\[Psi]=\>\"", 
   "no", "\"\< and comp\[Delta]=\>\"", 
   "no", "\"\<:\nAvoids computing the exponential part of the probability \
amplitude \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[ExponentialE]\), \(\[Psi]\)]\), \nand the \
solution to the Jacobi/geodesic-deviation equation \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\
\[Delta]x\), \(\[Mu]\)]\),\nwhich are not needed during the Newton-Raphson \
iteration.\n(One could in principle use \!\(\*SuperscriptBox[\(\[Delta]x\), \
\(\[Mu]\)]\) to compute the Jacobian and use it in the Newton-Raphson \
iteration,\nbut FindRoot converges quickly anyway, especially when using the \
extrapolation idea.)\n\ncompumu=\>\"", 
   "yes", "\"\<:\nThis gives a different way of computing \[Psi] when there \
is no EM field, \!\(\*SubscriptBox[\(A\), \(\[Mu]\)]\)=0.\nOne can then check \
that \[Psi]int and \[Psi]fin give the same results, to within numerical \
precision.\n\n\>\""}], "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.991052512567295*^9, 3.9910527589560413`*^9}, {
   3.991052823933756*^9, 3.9910529721603394`*^9}, {3.9910530055357075`*^9, 
   3.9910531318267403`*^9}, {3.99105334528409*^9, 3.9910533598859234`*^9}, {
   3.9910535045453205`*^9, 3.9910536450359135`*^9}, {3.9910536775964813`*^9, 
   3.991053842230982*^9}, {3.991053885567997*^9, 3.9910541645062923`*^9}, {
   3.991054209157049*^9, 3.9910542454338894`*^9}, {3.991054275540745*^9, 
   3.991054385656271*^9}, 3.9910545493306046`*^9, 3.9910545817315063`*^9, {
   3.991054933542742*^9, 3.991054939670231*^9}, {3.991054980765892*^9, 
   3.9910550254282055`*^9}, {3.991055055521551*^9, 3.9910550568064747`*^9}, {
   3.9910550963305874`*^9, 3.991055100776867*^9}, {3.991055140885515*^9, 
   3.991055161303564*^9}, {3.9910552548104286`*^9, 
   3.9910552551801643`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1dc57be7-0396-424e-a3e2-\
213b3187c51b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
